 <h2 id="opening-a-czi-read-only">Opening a CZI (read-only)</h2>
-<p>A CZI file can be opened in a context manager using a <a href="https://docs.python.org/3/library/os.html#os.PathLike">path-like-object</a>

-If this is correctly implemented, otherwise, lets start using file path
-only.</p>

 <h3 id="masks">Masks</h3>
-<p>Regions with no data will be filled by libCZI with the background
-color. There is therefore no way to tell between a pixel having the
-color of the background or being really background/invalid.</p>
-<p><em>A hacky way of figuring it out is to request the same data twice
-with different background colors.</em></p>
-<p>The real solution to this problem is by leveraging the mask data that
-exists in the CZI. Masks indicate regions with invalid or no data. There
-are two cases:<br />
-- simple case: there is no subblock at aspecific location - advanced
-case: there is a subblock with mask data, indicating that there are
-parts with invalid pixels</p>
-<p>However, there is no support (yet) for masks in libCZI. If we come to
-need it, it has to be implemented.</p>
